Can the euro be fixed?
Recently, French-German Finance Minister Scholz put the option of Greece's exit from the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict rules of the currency union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a big discussion about the principles of the euro, the governance model of the euro, and the foundation of the reason for the existence of the euro.
Two weeks before Scholz's proposal, European leaders had already noticed the report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President von der Leyen and her colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece made many decision-makers think it was necessary to go back to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they have to share the same currency?
Is it meaningful? Can there be a consensus on Greece's future?
A currency is like a nation, and its establishment requires a myth.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was a political price paid by Germany to France for reunification.
In fact, German reunification was the final step in a project that had been shaped and solved by the 1980s to address a long-standing issue.
European governments strongly opposed a floating exchange rate, considering it incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they did not want to maintain a long-term monetary mechanism dominated by the German central bank.
A true European currency based on German principles seems like the best solution.
In hindsight, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was struggling; France was undervalued and its economy was thriving.
Over the next decade, the imbalance gradually formed between the newly risen Germany and countries that experienced a credit boom due to low interest rates.
And with the global financial crisis of 2008, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark be overvalued again?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a housing bubble form in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analytical baseline to evaluate the impact of the euro.
But this is no reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has been disappointing, and the EU's political system must be held accountable for this.
What really matters is whether the common European currency is still important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginable (and if the eurozone were to collapse during a crisis, exacerbating the mutual recriminations between participating countries, the cost would only increase further).
In addition, abolishing the euro may unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke from Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is incomplete.
Logically, this is equivalent to advising a couple to stay married because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, is the euro still meaningful?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that a monetary union would promote economic integration and solidify Europe's long-term growth.
Instead, intra-eurozone trade and investment growth have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not further integrated the eurozone on the basis of monetary unity, building it into an economic superpower, but rather have tried to preserve their remaining power.
This may be in line with the logic of political compromise, but it is economically meaningless: Europe's vast internal market is one of its main assets, and it cannot afford to waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hope the euro becomes one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy requirements).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely achieved.
The euro's international usage ranks second only to the US dollar, which has helped Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believe that the institutions underlying the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the overall policy level of Europe is naturally higher than that of individual countries.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test arrived: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, thus performing worse than the US and the UK.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy and institutional reforms are necessary.
However, developing and implementing a plan requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debate over the Greek issue shows that Europe is still far from reaching a consensus: participating countries have contradictory analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and therefore their prescribed remedies are also contradictory.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University has observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases is severely constrained by the different infection patterns of countries.
Countries all favor joint action, but cannot form a unified plan because they have different opinions on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone is facing today.
Luckily, this problem is solvable, as major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of the banking union have proven.
The lack of consensus has not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, showing that institutional governance is indeed important.
However, reforms and actions have only begun recently, and were implemented only under the pressure of a severe crisis, making it clear to us how difficult it is to reach a consensus.
Europe cannot delay and pretend anymore.
The eurozone member states must agree on a schedule for governance and political reform to turn the currency union into a prosperity engine, otherwise they will sink into repeated debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose trust.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and grand reform.
Today, all major stakeholders have a duty to be clear about what they consider indispensable, what they cannot accept, and what they are willing to trade for what they want.
